# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: protein
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The process may be likened to how yeast ferments sugars to produce ethanol for wine, beer, or fuel, but the organisms that carry out the ABE fermentation are strictly anaerobic (obligate anaerobes).
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation produces solvents in a ratio of 3 parts acetone, 6 parts butanol to 1 part ethanol.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It usually uses a strain of bacteria from class Clostridia (family Clostridiaceae).
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] *Clostridium acetobutylicum* is the most well-studied and widely used.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although less effective, *Clostridium beijerinckii* and *Clostridium saccharobutylicum* bacterial strains have shown good results as well.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation pathway generally proceeds in two phases.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the initial acidogenesis phase, the cells grow exponentially and accumulate acetate and butyrate.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The low pH along with other factors then trigger a metabolic shift to the solventogenesis phase, in which acetate and butyrate are used to produce the solvents.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For gas stripping, the most common gases used are the off-gases from the fermentation itself, a mixture of carbon dioxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The production of butanol by biological means was first performed by Louis Pasteur in 1861.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1905, Austrian biochemist Franz Schardinger found that acetone could similarly be produced.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1910 Auguste Fernbach (1860–1939) developed a bacterial fermentation process using potato starch as a feedstock in the production of butanol.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Industrial exploitation of ABE fermentation started in 1916, during World War I, with Chaim Weizmann's isolation of Clostridium acetobutylicum, as described in U.S. patent 1315585.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Weizmann process was operated by Commercial Solvents Corporation from about 1920 to 1964 with plants in the US (Terre Haute, IN, and Peoria, IL), and Liverpool, England.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Peoria plant was the largest of the three.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It used molasses as feedstock and had 96 fermenters with a volume of 96,000 gallons each.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] After World War II, ABE fermentation became generally non-profitable, compared to the production of the same three solvents (acetone, butanol, ethanol) from petroleum.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] During the 1950s and 1960s, ABE fermentation was replaced by petroleum chemical plants.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Due to different raw material costs, ABE fermentation was viable in South Africa until the early 1980s, with the last plant closing in 1983.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd operated the last attempt to resurrect the process at scale but the plant closed in Minnesota in June 2019.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] A new ABE biorefinery has been developed in Scotland by Celtic Renewables Ltd and began production in 2023.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The key difference in the process is the use of low value spent materials or residues from other processes removing the variable costs of raw feedstock crops and materials.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The most critical aspect in biomass fermentation processes is related to its productivity.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation via *Clostridium beijerinckii* or *Clostridium acetobutylicum* for instance is characterized by product inhibition.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This means that there is a product concentration threshold that cannot be overcome, resulting in a product stream highly diluted in water.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, in order to have a comparable productivity and profitability with respect to the petrochemical processes, cost and energy effective solutions for the product purification sections are required to provide a significant product recovery at the desired purity.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the second half of the 20th century, these technologies allowed an increase in the final product concentration in the broth from 15 to 30 g/L, an increase in the final productivity from 0.46 to 4.6 g/(L*h) and an increase in the yield from 15 to 42%.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] From a compound purification perspective, the main criticalities in the ABE/W product recovery are due to the water–alcohol mixture's non-ideal interactions leading to homogeneous and heterogeneous azeotropic species, as shown by the ternary equilibrium diagram.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This causes the separation by standard distillation to be particularly impractical but, on the other hand, allows the exploitation of the liquid–liquid demixing region both for analogous and alternative separation processes.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Therefore, in order to enhance the ABE fermentation yield, mainly in situ product recovery systems have been developed.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] These include gas stripping, pervaporation, liquid–liquid extraction, distillation via Dividing Wall Column, membrane distillation, membrane separation, adsorption, and reverse osmosis.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd. implemented many of these technologies at an industrial scale.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, differently from crude oil feedstocks, biomasses nature fluctuates over the year's seasons and according to the geographical location.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] ABE fermentation is attracting renewed interest with a focus on butanol as a renewable biofuel.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Sustainability is by far the topic of major concern over the last years.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The energy challenge is the key point of the environmental friendly policies adopted by all the most developed and industrialized countries worldwide.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this purpose Horizon 2020, the biggest EU Research and Innovation programme, was funded by the European Union over the 2014–2020 period.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The International Energy Agency defines renewables as the centre of the transition to a less carbon-intensive and more sustainable energy system.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biofuels are believed to represent around 30% of energy consumption in transport by 2060.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Their role is particularly important in sectors which are difficult to decarbonise, such as aviation, shipping and other long-haul transport.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] That is why several bioprocesses have seen a renewed interest in recent years, both from a research and an industrial perspective.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, the ABE fermentation process has been reconsidered from a different perspective.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although it was originally conceived to produce acetone, it is considered as a suitable production pathway for biobutanol that has become the product of major interest.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biogenic butanol is a possible substitute of bioethanol or even better and it is already employed both as fuel additive and as pure fuel instead of standard gasoline because, differently from ethanol, it can be directly and efficiently used in gasoline engines.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, it has the advantage that it can be shipped and distributed through existing pipelines and filling stations.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Finally biobutanol is widely used as a direct solvent for paints, coatings, varnishes, resins, dyes, camphor, vegetable oils, fats, waxes, shellac, rubbers and alkaloids due to its higher energy density, lower volatility, and lower hygroscopicity.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It can be produced from different kinds of cellulosic biomass and can be used for further processing of advanced biofuels such as butyl levulinate as well.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The application of n-butanol in the production of butyl acrylate has a wide scope for its expansion, which in turn would help in increasing the consumption of n-butanol globally.
[src:protein/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Butyl acrylate was the biggest n-butanol application in 2014 and is projected to be worth US$3.9 billion by 2020.
[src:protein/actin-p01] An actin protein is the monomeric subunit of two types of filaments in cells: microfilaments, one of the three major components of the cytoskeleton, and thin filaments, part of the contractile apparatus in muscle cells.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It can be present as either a free monomer called **G-actin** (globular) or as part of a linear polymer microfilament called **F-actin** (filamentous), both of which are essential for such important cellular functions as the mobility and contraction of cells during cell division.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin participates in many important cellular processes, including muscle contraction, cell motility, cell division and cytokinesis, vesicle and organelle movement, cell signaling, and the establishment and maintenance of cell junctions and cell shape.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Many of these processes are mediated by extensive and intimate interactions of actin with cellular membranes.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In vertebrates, three main groups of actin isoforms, alpha, beta, and gamma have been identified.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The alpha actins, found in muscle tissues, are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The beta and gamma actins coexist in most cell types as components of the cytoskeleton, and as mediators of internal cell motility.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It is believed that the diverse range of structures formed by actin enabling it to fulfill such a large range of functions is regulated through the binding of tropomyosin along the filaments.
[src:protein/actin-p01] A cell's ability to dynamically form microfilaments provides the scaffolding that allows it to rapidly remodel itself in response to its environment or to the organism's internal signals, for example, to increase cell membrane absorption or increase cell adhesion in order to form cell tissue.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Other enzymes or organelles such as cilia can be anchored to this scaffolding in order to control the deformation of the external cell membrane, which allows endocytosis and cytokinesis.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It can also produce movement either by itself or with the help of molecular motors.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin therefore contributes to processes such as the intracellular transport of vesicles and organelles as well as muscular contraction and cellular migration.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It therefore plays an important role in embryogenesis, the healing of wounds, and the invasivity of cancer cells.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The evolutionary origin of actin can be traced to prokaryotic cells, which have equivalent proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin homologs from prokaryotes and archaea polymerize into different helical or linear filaments consisting of one or multiple strands.
[src:protein/actin-p01] However the in-strand contacts and nucleotide binding sites are preserved in prokaryotes and in archaea.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Lastly, actin plays an important role in the control of gene expression.
[src:protein/actin-p01] A large number of illnesses and diseases are caused by mutations in alleles of the genes that regulate the production of actin or of its associated proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The production of actin is also key to the process of infection by some pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Mutations in the different genes that regulate actin production in humans can cause muscular diseases, variations in the size and function of the heart as well as deafness.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The make-up of the cytoskeleton is also related to the pathogenicity of intracellular bacteria and viruses, particularly in the processes related to evading the actions of the immune system.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin's primary role in the cell is to form linear polymers called microfilaments that serve various functions in the cell's structure, trafficking networks, migration, and replication.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The multifaceted role of actin relies on a few of the microfilaments' properties: First, the formation of actin filaments is reversible, and their function often involves undergoing rapid polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Second, microfilaments are polarized – i.e. the two ends of a filament are distinct from one another.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Third, actin filaments can bind to many other proteins, which together help modify and organize microfilaments for their diverse functions.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin is extremely abundant in most cells, comprising 1–5% of the total protein mass of most cells, and 10% of muscle cells.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The actin protein is found in both the cytoplasm and the cell nucleus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Its location is regulated by cell membrane signal transduction pathways that integrate the stimuli that a cell receives stimulating the restructuring of the actin networks in response.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The role of actin as a regulator of chemical processes in the cell cytoplasm was proposed.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The cytoplasm is viscous, crowded, and heterogeneous, a dynamic complex, a gel-like substance that restricts free diffusion but is capable of managing a myriad of reactions at any moment.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The high capacity of the cytoplasm to perform complex chemical reactions can be explained by a two-phase system of organization, in which catalytic complexes are immobilized in the elastic solid phase (cytomatrix), thereby overcoming spatial hindrances and crowding .
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nutrients and substrates can be delivered by liquid-phase (cytosol) flux, and the motor protein actin provides the driving force for cytomatrix mechanics.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Approximately 150 actin-binding and regulatory proteins fine-tune metabolic processes in the cytoplasm, thereby overcoming cytoplasmic viscosity.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The energy source for actin dynamics in normal physiological conditions is mitochondria.
[src:protein/actin-p01] However, cancer cells, due to their high metabolic rate, require additional ATP, which can be supplied by glycolysis (the Warburg effect).
[src:protein/actin-p01] There are a number of different types of actin with slightly different structures and functions. α-actin is found exclusively in muscle fibres, while β- and γ-actin are found in other cells.
[src:protein/actin-p01] As the latter types have a high turnover rate the majority of them are found outside permanent structures.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin's cytoskeleton is key to the processes of endocytosis, cytokinesis, determination of cell polarity and morphogenesis in yeasts.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In addition to relying on actin, these processes involve 20 or 30 associated proteins, which all have a high degree of evolutionary conservation, along with many signalling molecules.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Together these elements allow a spatially and temporally modulated assembly that defines a cell's response to both internal and external stimuli.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Yeasts contain three main elements that are associated with actin: patches, cables, and rings.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Despite not being present for long, these structures are subject to a dynamic equilibrium due to continual polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Plant genome studies have revealed the existence of protein isovariants within the actin family of genes.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Within *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a model organism, there are ten types of actin, six profilins, and dozens of myosins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This diversity is explained by the evolutionary necessity of possessing variants that slightly differ in their temporal and spatial expression.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The majority of these proteins were jointly expressed in the tissue analysed.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin networks are distributed throughout the cytoplasm of cells that have been cultivated *in vitro*.
[src:protein/actin-p01] There is a concentration of the network around the nucleus that is connected via spokes to the cellular cortex, this network is highly dynamic, with a continuous polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Even though the majority of plant cells have a cell wall that defines their morphology, their microfilaments can generate sufficient force to achieve a number of cellular activities, such as the cytoplasmic currents generated by the microfilaments and myosin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in the movement of organelles and in cellular morphogenesis, which involve cell division as well as the elongation and differentiation of the cell.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nuclear actin was first noticed and described in 1977 by Clark and Merriam.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Authors describe a protein present in the nuclear fraction, obtained from *Xenopus laevis* oocytes, which shows the same features as skeletal muscle actin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The actin sequence does not contain a nuclear localization signal.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The small size of actin (about 43 kDa) allows it to enter the nucleus by passive diffusion.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The import of actin into the nucleus (probably in a complex with cofilin) is facilitated by the import protein importin 9.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Low levels of actin in the nucleus seems to be important, because actin has two nuclear export signals (NES) in its sequence.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Microinjected actin is quickly removed from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin is exported at least in two ways, through exportin 1 and exportin 6.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Specific modifications, such as SUMOylation, allows for nuclear actin retention.
[src:protein/actin-p01] A mutation preventing SUMOylation causes rapid export of beta actin from the nucleus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nuclear actin exists mainly as a monomer, but can also form dynamic oligomers and short polymers.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nuclear actin organization varies in different cell types.
[src:protein/actin-p01] For example, in *Xenopus* oocytes (with higher nuclear actin level in comparison to somatic cells) actin forms filaments, which stabilize nucleus architecture.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These filaments can be observed under the microscope thanks to fluorophore-conjugated phalloidin staining.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In somatic cell nuclei, however, actin filaments cannot be observed using this technique.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The DNase I inhibition assay, the only test which allows the quantification of the polymerized actin directly in biological samples, has revealed that endogenous nuclear actin indeed occurs mainly in a monomeric form.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Precisely controlled level of actin in the cell nucleus, lower than in the cytoplasm, prevents the formation of filaments.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The polymerization is also reduced by the limited access to actin monomers, which are bound in complexes with ABPs, mainly cofilin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Different isoforms of actin are present in the cell nucleus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The level of actin isoforms may change in response to stimulation of cell growth or arrest of proliferation and transcriptional activity.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Research on nuclear actin is focused on isoform beta.
[src:protein/actin-p01] However the use of antibodies directed against different actin isoforms allows identifying not only the cytoplasmic beta in the cell nucleus, but also alpha- and gamma-actin in certain cell types.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The presence of different isoforms of actin may have a significant effect on its function in nuclear processes, as the level of individual isoforms can be controlled independently.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Functions of actin in the nucleus are associated with its ability to polymerize and interact with various ABPs and with structural elements of the nucleus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Due to its ability to undergo conformational changes and interaction with many proteins, actin acts as a regulator of formation and activity of protein complexes such as transcriptional complex.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in cell movement.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Several different types of protrusions mediated directly or indirectly by actin are involved in cell migration in different ways, with the most important ones being lamellipodia, filopodia, invadopodia and blebs.
[src:protein/actin-p01] A meshwork of actin filaments marks the forward edge of a moving cell, and the polymerization of new actin filaments pushes the cell membrane forward in protrusions called lamellipodia.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These membrane protrusions then attach to the substrate, forming structures known as focal adhesions that connect to the actin network.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Once attached, the rear of the cell body contracts squeezing its contents forward past the adhesion point.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Once the adhesion point has moved to the rear of the cell, the cell disassembles it, allowing the rear of the cell to move forward.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Filopodia are thin extensions of the plasma membrane that contain parallel bundles of actin filaments, in contrast to the branched actin structures of lamellipodia.
[src:protein/actin-p01] They serve an exploratory role, being used by cells to probe their environment.
[src:protein/actin-p01] While the presence of filopodia is linked to enhanced cell migration, they are not directly involved in cell body displacement.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Invadopodia are actin-driven membrane protrusions that help to degrade the extracellular matrix.
[src:protein/actin-p01] They are used by cancer cells for cell invasion, particularly to help them cross the basement membrane.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The matrix degradation takes place by transporting vesicles containing matrix-degrading proteins to the invadopodia where the proteins are released via exocytosis.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Blebs are spherical membrane protrusions that are involved in both apoptosis and cell movement.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The driving force behind bleb extension is hydrostatic pressure, rather than actin filament elongation which drives lamellipodia, filopodia and invadopodia extension.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Blebs are formed by actomyosin contraction, which causes the delamination of the plasma membrane from the actin cortex or a focal rupture of the actin cortex.
[src:protein/actin-p01] They are then stabilized via actin cortex reassembly and finally retracted via actomyosin contraction.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In migrating cells a front-rear polarity is established, with bleb formation restricted to the leading edge, allowing for directed movement.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In addition to the physical force generated by actin polymerization, microfilaments facilitate the movement of various intracellular components by serving as the roadway along which a family of motor proteins called myosins travel.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin plays a particularly prominent role in muscle cells, which consist largely of repeated bundles of actin and myosin II.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Each repeated unit – called a sarcomere – consists of two sets of oppositely oriented F-actin strands ("thin filaments"), interlaced with bundles of myosin ("thick filaments").
[src:protein/actin-p01] The two sets of actin strands are oriented with their (+) ends embedded in either end of the sarcomere in delimiting structures called Z-disks.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The myosin fibrils are in the middle between the sets of actin filaments, with strands facing in both directions.
[src:protein/actin-p01] When the muscle contracts, the myosin threads move along the actin filaments towards the (+) end, pulling the ends of the sarcomere together and shortening it by around 70% of its length.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In order to move along the actin thread, myosin must hydrolyze ATP; thus ATP serves as the energy source for muscle contraction.
[src:protein/actin-p01] At times of rest, the proteins tropomyosin and troponin bind to the actin filaments, preventing the attachment of myosin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] When an activation signal (i.e. an action potential) arrives at the muscle fiber, it triggers the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum into the cytosol.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The resulting spike in cytosolic calcium rapidly releases tropomyosin and troponin from the actin thread, allowing myosin to bind, and muscle contraction to begin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In the final stages of cell division, many cells form a ring of actin at the cell's midpoint.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This ring, aptly called the "contractile ring", uses a similar mechanism as muscle fibers where myosin II pulls along the actin ring, causing it to contract.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This contraction cleaves the parent cell into two, completing cytokinesis.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The contractile ring is composed of actin, myosin, anillin, and α-actinin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In the fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, actin is actively formed in the constricting ring with the participation of Arp3, the formin Cdc12, profilin, and WASp, along with preformed microfilaments.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Once the ring has been constructed the structure is maintained by a continual assembly and disassembly that, aided by the Arp2/3 complex and formins, is key to one of the central processes of cytokinesis.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin-myosin pairs can also participate in the trafficking of various membrane vesicles and organelles within the cell.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Myosin V is activated by binding to various cargo receptors on organelles, and then moves along an actin filament towards the (+) end, pulling its cargo along with it.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These nonconventional myosins use ATP hydrolysis to transport cargo, such as vesicles and organelles, in a directed fashion much faster than diffusion.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Myosin V walks towards the barbed end of actin filaments, while myosin VI walks toward the pointed end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Most actin filaments are arranged with the barbed end toward the cellular membrane and the pointed end toward the cellular interior.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This arrangement allows myosin V to be an effective motor for the export of cargos, and myosin VI to be an effective motor for import.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The traditional image of actin's function relates it to the maintenance of the cytoskeleton and, therefore, the organization and movement of organelles, as well as the determination of a cell's shape.
[src:protein/actin-p01] However, actin has a wider role in eukaryotic cell physiology, in addition to similar functions in prokaryotes.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Monomeric actin, or G-actin, has a globular structure consisting of two lobes separated by a deep cleft.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The bottom of the cleft represents the "ATPase fold", a structure conserved among ATP and GTP-binding proteins that binds to a magnesium ion and a molecule of ATP.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Binding of ATP or ADP is required to stabilize each actin monomer; without one of these molecules bound, actin quickly becomes denatured.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The X-ray crystallography model of actin that was produced by Kabsch from the striated muscle tissue of rabbits is the most commonly used in structural studies as it was the first to be purified.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The G-actin crystallized by Kabsch is approximately 67 x 40 x 37 Å in size, has a molecular mass of 41,785 Da and an estimated isoelectric point of 4.8.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Elzinga and co-workers first determined the complete peptide sequence for this type of actin in 1973, with later work by the same author adding further detail to the model.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Its N-terminus is highly acidic and starts with an acetyled aspartate in its amino group, while its C-terminus is alkaline and is formed by a phenylalanine preceded by a cysteine, which has a degree of functional importance.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Both extremes are in close proximity within the I-subdomain.
[src:protein/actin-p01] An anomalous *N*τ-methylhistidine is located at position 73.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The tertiary structure is formed by two domains known as the large and the small, which are separated by a cleft centred around the location of the bond with ATP-ADP+Pi.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Below this there is a deeper notch called a "groove".
[src:protein/actin-p01] In the native state, despite their names, both have a comparable depth.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The normal convention in topological studies means that a protein is shown with the biggest domain on the left-hand side and the smallest domain on the right-hand side.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In this position the smaller domain is in turn divided into two: subdomain I (lower position, residues 1–32, 70–144, and 338–374) and subdomain II (upper position, residues 33–69).
[src:protein/actin-p01] The larger domain is also divided in two: subdomain III (lower, residues 145–180 and 270–337) and subdomain IV (higher, residues 181–269).
[src:protein/actin-p01] The exposed areas of subdomains I and III are referred to as the "barbed" ends, while the exposed areas of domains II and IV are termed the "pointed" ends.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This nomenclature refers to the fact that, due to the small mass of subdomain II actin is polar; the importance of this will be discussed below in the discussion on assembly dynamics.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Some authors call the subdomains Ia, Ib, IIa, and IIb, respectively.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The most notable supersecondary structure is a five chain beta sheet that is composed of a β-meander and a β-α-β clockwise unit.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It is present in both domains suggesting that the protein arose from gene duplication.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Under various conditions, G-actin molecules polymerize into longer threads called "filamentous-" or "F-actin".
[src:protein/actin-p01] These F-actin threads are typically composed of two helical strands of actin wound around each other, forming a 7 to 9 nanometer wide helix that repeats every 72 nanometers (or every 14 G-actin subunits).
[src:protein/actin-p01] In F-actin threads, G-actin molecules are all oriented in the same direction.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The two ends of the F-actin thread are distinct from one another.
[src:protein/actin-p01] At one end – designated the (−) end – the ATP-binding cleft of the terminal actin molecule is facing outward.
[src:protein/actin-p01] At the opposite end – designated (+) – the ATP-binding cleft is buried in the filament, contacting the neighboring actin molecule.
[src:protein/actin-p01] As F-actin threads grow, new molecules tend to join at the (+) end of an existing F-actin strand.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Conversely, threads tend to shrink by shedding actin monomers from the strand's (−) end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Some proteins, such as cofilin appear to increase the angle of turn, but again this could be interpreted as the establishment of different structural states.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These could be important in the polymerization process.
[src:protein/actin-p01] There is less agreement regarding measurements of the turn radius and filament thickness: while the first models assigned a length of 25 Å, current X-ray diffraction data, backed up by cryo-electron microscopy suggests a length of 23.7 Å.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These studies have shown the precise contact points between monomers.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Some are formed with units of the same chain, between the "barbed" end on one monomer and the "pointed" end of the next one.
[src:protein/actin-p01] While the monomers in adjacent chains make lateral contact through projections from subdomain IV, with the most important projections being those formed by the C-terminus and the hydrophobic link formed by three bodies involving residues 39–42, 201–203, and 286.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This model suggests that a filament is formed by monomers in a "sheet" formation, in which the subdomains turn about themselves, this form is also found in the bacterial actin homologue MreB.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The terms "pointed" and "barbed" referring to the two ends of the microfilaments derive from their appearance under transmission electron microscopy when samples are examined following a preparation technique called "decoration".
[src:protein/actin-p01] This method consists of the addition of myosin S1 fragments to tissue that has been fixed with tannic acid.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This myosin forms polar bonds with actin monomers, giving rise to a configuration that looks like arrows with feather fletchings along its shaft, where the shaft is the actin and the fletchings are the myosin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Following this logic, the end of the microfilament that does not have any protruding myosin is called the point of the arrow (− end) and the other end is called the barbed end (+ end).
[src:protein/actin-p01] A S1 fragment is composed of the head and neck domains of myosin II.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Under physiological conditions, G-actin (the monomer form) is transformed to F-actin (the polymer form) by ATP, where the role of ATP is essential.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The helical F-actin filament found in muscles also contains a tropomyosin molecule, which is a 40 nanometre long protein that is wrapped around the F-actin helix.
[src:protein/actin-p01] During the resting phase the tropomyosin covers the actin's active sites so that the actin-myosin interaction cannot take place and produce muscular contraction.
[src:protein/actin-p01] There are other protein molecules bound to the tropomyosin thread, these are the troponins that have three polymers: troponin I, troponin T, and troponin C.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Unlike other polymers, such as DNA, whose constituent elements are bound together with covalent bonds, the monomers of actin filaments are assembled by weaker bonds.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The lateral bonds with neighbouring monomers resolve this anomaly, which in theory should weaken the structure as they can be broken by thermal agitation.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In addition, the weak bonds give the advantage that the filament ends can easily release or incorporate monomers.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This means that the filaments can be rapidly remodelled and can change cellular structure in response to an environmental stimulus.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Which, along with the biochemical mechanism by which it is brought about is known as the "assembly dynamic".
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin can spontaneously acquire a large part of its tertiary structure.
[src:protein/actin-p01] However, the way it acquires its fully functional form from its newly synthesized native form is special and almost unique in protein chemistry.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The reason for this special route could be the need to avoid the presence of incorrectly folded actin monomers, which could be toxic as they can act as inefficient polymerization terminators.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nevertheless, it is key to establishing the stability of the cytoskeleton, and additionally, it is an essential process for coordinating the cell cycle.
[src:protein/actin-p01] CCT is required in order to ensure that folding takes place correctly.
[src:protein/actin-p01] CCT is a group II chaperonin, a large protein complex that assists in the folding of other proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] CCT is formed of a double ring of eight different subunits (hetero-octameric) and it differs from group I chaperonins like GroEL, which is found in Eubacteria and in eukaryotic organelles, as it does not require a co-chaperone to act as a lid over the central catalytic cavity.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Substrates bind to CCT through specific domains.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It was initially thought that it only bound with actin and tubulin, although recent immunoprecipitation studies have shown that it interacts with a large number of polypeptides, which possibly function as substrates.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It acts through ATP-dependent conformational changes that on occasion require several rounds of liberation and catalysis in order to complete a reaction.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In order to successfully complete their folding, both actin and tubulin need to interact with another protein called prefoldin, which is a heterohexameric complex (formed by six distinct subunits), in an interaction that is so specific that the molecules have coevolved.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin forms a complex with prefoldin while it is still being formed, when it is approximately 145 amino acids long, specifically those at the N-terminal.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Different recognition sub-units are used for actin or tubulin although there is some overlap.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In actin the subunits that bind with prefoldin are probably PFD3 and PFD4, which bind in two places one between residues 60–79 and the other between residues 170–198.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The actin is recognized, loaded, and delivered to the cytosolic chaperonin (CCT) in an open conformation by the inner end of prefoldin's "tentacles" (see the image and note).
[src:protein/actin-p01] The contact when actin is delivered is so brief that a tertiary complex is not formed, immediately freeing the prefoldin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The CCT then causes actin's sequential folding by forming bonds with its subunits rather than simply enclosing it in its cavity.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This is why it possesses specific recognition areas in its apical β-domain.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The first stage in the folding consists of the recognition of residues 245–249.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Next, other determinants establish contact.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Both actin and tubulin bind to CCT in open conformations in the absence of ATP.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In actin's case, two subunits are bound during each conformational change, whereas for tubulin binding takes place with four subunits.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin has specific binding sequences, which interact with the δ and β-CCT subunits or with δ-CCT and ε-CCT.
[src:protein/actin-p01] After AMP-PNP is bound to CCT the substrates move within the chaperonin's cavity.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It also seems that in the case of actin, the CAP protein is required as a possible cofactor in actin's final folding states.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The exact manner by which this process is regulated is still not fully understood, but it is known that the protein PhLP3 (a protein similar to phosducin) inhibits its activity through the formation of a tertiary complex.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin is an ATPase, which means that it is an enzyme that hydrolyzes ATP.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This group of enzymes is characterised by their slow reaction rates.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It is known that this ATPase is "active", that is, its speed increases by some 40,000 times when the actin forms part of a filament.
[src:protein/actin-p01] A reference value for this rate of hydrolysis under ideal conditions is around 0.3 s−1.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Then, the Pi remains bound to the actin next to the ADP for a long time, until it is cooperatively liberated from the interior of the filament.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The exact molecular details of the catalytic mechanism are still not fully understood.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Although there is much debate on this issue, it seems certain that a "closed" conformation is required for the hydrolysis of ATP, and it is thought that the residues that are involved in the process move to the appropriate distance.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The glutamic acid Glu137 is one of the key residues, which is located in subdomain 1.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Its function is to bind the water molecule that produces a nucleophilic attack on the ATP's γ-phosphate bond, while the nucleotide is strongly bound to subdomains 3 and 4.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The slowness of the catalytic process is due to the large distance and skewed position of the water molecule in relation to the reactant.
[src:protein/actin-p01] It is highly likely that the conformational change produced by the rotation of the domains between actin's G and F forms moves the Glu137 closer allowing its hydrolysis.
[src:protein/actin-p01] This model suggests that the polymerization and ATPase's function would be decoupled straight away.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The "open" to "closed" transformation between G and F forms and its implications on the relative motion of several key residues and the formation of water wires have been characterized in molecular dynamics and QM/MM simulations.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin filaments are often rapidly assembled and disassembled, allowing them to generate force and support cell movement.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Assembly classically occurs in three steps.
[src:protein/actin-p01] First, the "nucleation phase", in which two to three G-actin molecules slowly join to form a small oligomer that will nucleate further growth.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Second, the "elongation phase", when the actin filament rapidly grows by the addition of many actin molecules to both ends.
[src:protein/actin-p01] As the filament grows, actin molecules are added to the (+) end of the filament around 10 times faster than to the (−) end, and so filaments tend to primarily grow at the (+) end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Third, the "steady-state phase", where an equillibrium is reached as actin molecules join and leave the filament at the same rate, maintaining the filament's length.
[src:protein/actin-p01] While the filament's length remains constant in the steady-state phase, new molecules are constantly being added to the (+) end and falling off the (−) end, a phenomenon called "treadmilling" as a given actin molecule would appear to move along the strand.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In isolation, whether a filament will grow or shrink, and how quickly, are determined by the concentration of G-actin around the filament; however, in cells, the dynamics of actin filaments are heavily influenced by various actin-binding proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The actin cytoskeleton *in vivo* is not exclusively composed of actin, other proteins are required for its formation, continuance, and function.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These proteins are called actin-binding proteins and they are involved in actin's polymerization, depolymerization, stability, and organisation.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The diversity of these proteins is such that actin is thought to be the protein that takes part in the greatest number of protein-protein interactions.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The nucleation of new actin filaments – the rate-limiting step in actin polymerization – is aided by actin-nucleating proteins such as formins (like formin-2) and the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Formins help to nucleate long actin filaments.
[src:protein/actin-p01] They bind two free actin-ATP molecules, bringing them together.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Then as the filament begins to grow, formin moves along the (+) end of the growing filament, all the while recruiting actin-binding proteins that promote filament growth, and excluding capping proteins that would block filament extension.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Branches in actin filaments are typically nucleated by the Arp2/3 complex in concert with nucleation promoting factors.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Nucleation promoting factors bind two free G-actin molecules, then recruit and activate the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The activated Arp2/3 complex attaches to an existing actin filament, and uses the two bound G-actin molecules to nucleate a new actin filament branching off of the old one at a 70° angle.
[src:protein/actin-p01] As filaments grow, the pool of available G-actin molecules is managed by G-actin-binding proteins such as profilin and thymosin β-4.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Profilin ensures a supply of available actin-ATP by binding to ADP-bound G-actin and promoting the exchange of ADP for ATP.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Profilin's binding to the actin molecule physically blocks its addition to a filament's (−) end, but permits it to join the (+) end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Once the actin-ATP has joined the filament, profilin releases it.
[src:protein/actin-p01] As formins promote the nucleation and extension of new actin filaments, they recruit profilin to the area, increasing the local concentration of actin-ATP to boost filament growth.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In contrast, thymosin β-4 binds and sequesters actin-ATP, preventing it from joining a microfilament.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Once an actin fiber is established, the dynamics of its growth or collapse are influenced by numerous proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Existing strands can be interrupted by filament cleaving proteins, such as cofilin and gelsolin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Cofilin binds along two actin-ADP molecules in a filament, forcing a movement that destabilizes the filament and causes it to break.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Gelsolin inserts itself between actin molecules in a filament, disrupting the filament.
[src:protein/actin-p01] After the filament breaks, gelsolin remains attached to the new (+) end, preventing it from growing, thus forcing its disassembly.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Other proteins bind to the ends of actin filaments, stabilizing them.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These are called "capping proteins" and include CapZ and tropomodulin.
[src:protein/actin-p01] CapZ binds the (+) end of a filament, preventing further addition or loss of actin from that end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Tropomodulin binds to a filament's (−) end, again preventing addition or loss of molecule's at that end.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Tropomodulin is typically found in cells that require extremely stable actin filaments, such as those in muscle and red blood cells.
[src:protein/actin-p01] These actin binding proteins are typically regulated by various cellular signals to control actin assembly dynamics in different cellular locations.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Formins, for example, are typically folded in an inactive conformation until they're activated by the binding of the small GTPase Rho.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Actin branching at the cell membrane is important for cell movement, and so the plasma membrane lipid PIP2 activates the nucleation promoting factor WASp and inhibits CapZ.
[src:protein/actin-p01] WASp is also activated by the small GTPase Cdc42, while another nucleation promoting factor WAVE is activated by the GTPase Rac1.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Although most yeasts have only a single actin gene, higher eukaryotes, in general, express several isoforms of actin encoded by a family of related genes.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Mammals have at least six actin isoforms coded by separate genes, which are divided into three classes – alpha, beta, and gamma – according to their isoelectric points.
[src:protein/actin-p01] In general, alpha actins are found in muscle (α-skeletal, α-aortic smooth, α-cardiac), whereas beta and gamma isoforms are prominent in non-muscle cells (β-cytoplasmic, γ1-cytoplasmic, γ2-enteric smooth).
[src:protein/actin-p01] Although the amino acid sequences and *in vitro* properties of the isoforms are highly similar, these isoforms cannot completely substitute for one another *in vivo*.
[src:protein/actin-p01] Plants contains more than 60 actin genes and pseudogenes.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The typical actin gene has an approximately 100-nucleotide 5' UTR, a 1200-nucleotide translated region, and a 200-nucleotide 3' UTR.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The majority of actin genes are interrupted by introns, with up to six introns in any of 19 well-characterised locations.
[src:protein/actin-p01] The high conservation of the family makes actin the favoured model for studies comparing the introns-early and introns-late models of intron evolution.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Actin and closely related proteins are present in all organisms, suggesting the common ancestor of all life on Earth had actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Actin is one of the most conserved proteins throughout the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The sequences of actin proteins from animals and amoebae are 80% identical despite being separated by approximately one billion years of evolution.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Many unicellular eukaryotes have a single actin gene, while multicellular eukaryotes often have several closely related genes that serve specialized functions.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Humans have six; plants have 10 or more.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In addition to actin, eukaryotes have a large family of actin-related proteins, or "Arps", that share a common ancestor with actin and are called Arp1–Arp11, with Arp1 the most closely related to actin, and Arp11 the least.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Bacteria encode three types of actin: MreB influences cell shape, FtsA cell division, and ParM separation of large plasmids.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Some archaea have a bacteria-like MreB gene, while others have an actin gene that more closely resembles eukaryote actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The eukaryotic cytoskeleton of organisms among all taxonomic groups have similar components to actin and tubulin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] For example, the protein that is coded by the *ACTG2* gene in humans is completely equivalent to the homologues present in rats and mice, even though at a nucleotide level the similarity decreases to 92%.
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, there are major differences with the equivalents in prokaryotes (FtsZ and MreB), where the similarity between nucleotide sequences is between 40 and 50% among different bacteria and archaea species.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Some authors suggest that the ancestral protein that gave rise to the model eukaryotic actin resembles the proteins present in modern bacterial cytoskeletons.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Some authors point out that the behaviour of actin, tubulin, and histone, a protein involved in the stabilization and regulation of DNA, are similar in their ability to bind nucleotides and in their ability of take advantage of Brownian motion.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It has also been suggested that they all have a common ancestor.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Therefore, evolutionary processes resulted in the diversification of ancestral proteins into the varieties present today, conserving, among others, actins as efficient molecules that were able to tackle essential ancestral biological processes, such as endocytosis.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The Arp2/3 complex is widely found in all eukaryotic organisms.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton contains proteins that are highly similar to actin monomers and polymers.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The bacterial protein MreB polymerizes into thin non-helical filaments and occasionally into helical structures similar to F-actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Furthermore, its crystalline structure is very similar to that of G-actin (in terms of its three-dimensional conformation), there are even similarities between the MreB protofilaments and F-actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton also contains the FtsZ proteins, which are similar to tubulin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Bacteria therefore possess a cytoskeleton with homologous elements to actin (for example, MreB, AlfA, ParM, FtsA, and MamK), even though the amino acid sequence of these proteins diverges from that present in animal cells.
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, such proteins have a high degree of structural similarity to eukaryotic actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The highly dynamic microfilaments formed by the aggregation of MreB and ParM are essential to cell viability and they are involved in cell morphogenesis, chromosome segregation, and cell polarity.
[src:protein/actin-p02] ParM is an actin homologue that is coded in a plasmid and it is involved in the regulation of plasmid DNA.
[src:protein/actin-p02] ParMs from different bacterial plasmids can form astonishingly diverse helical structures comprising two or four strands to maintain faithful plasmid inheritance.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In archaea the homologue Ta0583 is even more similar to the eukaryotic actins.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The majority of mammals possess six different actin genes.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Of these, two code for the cytoskeleton (*ACTB* and *ACTG1*) while the other four are involved in skeletal striated muscle (*ACTA1*), smooth muscle tissue (*ACTA2*), intestinal muscles (*ACTG2*) and cardiac muscle (*ACTC1*).
[src:protein/actin-p02] The actin in the cytoskeleton is involved in the pathogenic mechanisms of many infectious agents, including HIV.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The vast majority of the mutations that affect actin are point mutations that have a dominant effect, with the exception of six mutations involved in nemaline myopathy.
[src:protein/actin-p02] This is because in many cases the mutant of the actin monomer acts as a "cap" by preventing the elongation of F-actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The mutation alters the structure and function of skeletal muscles producing one of three forms of myopathy: type 3 nemaline myopathy, congenital myopathy with an excess of thin myofilaments (CM) and congenital myopathy with fibre type disproportion (CMFTD).
[src:protein/actin-p02] Mutations have also been found that produce core myopathies.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Although their phenotypes are similar, in addition to typical nemaline myopathy some specialists distinguish another type of myopathy called actinic nemaline myopathy.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In the former, clumps of actin form instead of the typical rods.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It is important to state that a patient can show more than one of these phenotypes in a biopsy.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The most common symptoms consist of a typical facial morphology (myopathic facies), muscular weakness, a delay in motor development and respiratory difficulties.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The course of the illness, its gravity, and the age at which it appears are all variable and overlapping forms of myopathy are also found.
[src:protein/actin-p02] A symptom of nemaline myopathy is that "nemaline rods" appear in differing places in type 1 muscle fibres.
[src:protein/actin-p02] These rods are non-pathognomonic structures that have a similar composition to the Z disks found in the sarcomere.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The pathogenesis of this myopathy is very varied.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Many mutations occur in the region of actin's indentation near to its nucleotide binding sites, while others occur in Domain 2, or in the areas where interaction occurs with associated proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p02] This goes some way to explain the great variety of clumps that form in these cases, such as Nemaline or Intranuclear Bodies or Zebra Bodies.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Changes in actin's folding occur in nemaline myopathy as well as changes in its aggregation and there are also changes in the expression of other associated proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In some variants where intranuclear bodies are found the changes in the folding masks the nucleus's protein exportation signal so that the accumulation of actin's mutated form occurs in the cell nucleus.
[src:protein/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that mutations to *ACTA1* that give rise to a CFTDM have a greater effect on sarcomeric function than on its structure.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Recent investigations have tried to understand this apparent paradox, which suggests there is no clear correlation between the number of rods and muscular weakness.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It appears that some mutations are able to induce a greater apoptosis rate in type II muscular fibres.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The *ACTC1* gene codes for the α-actin isoform present in heart muscle.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It was first sequenced by Hamada and co-workers in 1982, when it was found that it is interrupted by five introns.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It was the first of the six genes where alleles were found that were implicated in pathological processes.
[src:protein/actin-p02] A number of structural disorders associated with point mutations of this gene have been described that cause malfunctioning of the heart, such as Type 1R dilated cardiomyopathy and Type 11 hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Certain defects of the atrial septum have been described recently that could also be related to these mutations.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Two cases of dilated cardiomyopathy have been studied involving a substitution of highly conserved amino acids belonging to the protein domains that bind and intersperse with the Z discs.
[src:protein/actin-p02] This has led to the theory that the dilation is produced by a defect in the transmission of contractile force in the myocytes.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The mutations in ACTC1 are responsible for at least 5% of hypertrophic cardiomyopathies.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Recent studies have discovered ACTC1 mutations that are implicated in two other pathological processes: Infantile idiopathic restrictive cardiomyopathy, and noncompaction of the left ventricular myocardium.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The *ACTG1* locus codes for the cytosolic γ-actin protein that is responsible for the formation of cytoskeletal microfilaments.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It contains six exons, giving rise to 22 different mRNAs, which produce four complete isoforms whose form of expression is probably dependent on the type of tissue they are found in.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It also has two different DNA promoters.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It has been noted that the sequences translated from this locus and from that of β-actin are very similar to the predicted ones, suggesting a common ancestral sequence that suffered duplication and genetic conversion.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In terms of pathology, it has been associated with processes such as amyloidosis, retinitis pigmentosa, infection mechanisms, kidney diseases, and various types of congenital hearing loss.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Six autosomal-dominant point mutations in the sequence have been found to cause various types of hearing loss, particularly sensorineural hearing loss linked to the DFNA 20/26 locus.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It seems that they affect the stereocilia of the ciliated cells present in the inner ear's Organ of Corti. β-actin is the most abundant protein found in human tissue, but it is not very abundant in ciliated cells, which explains the location of the pathology.
[src:protein/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that the majority of these mutations affect the areas involved in linking with other proteins, particularly actomyosin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Some experiments have suggested that the pathological mechanism for this type of hearing loss relates to the F-actin in the mutations being more sensitive to cofilin than normal.
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, although there is no record of any case, it is known that γ-actin is also expressed in skeletal muscles, and although it is present in small quantities, model organisms have shown that its absence can give rise to myopathies.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Some infectious agents use actin, especially cytoplasmic actin, in their life cycle.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In addition to the previously cited example, actin polymerization is stimulated in the initial steps of the internalization of some viruses, notably HIV, by, for example, inactivating the cofilin complex.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The role that actin plays in the invasion process of cancer cells has still not been determined.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In conditions of high lipoperoxidation, actin has been shown to be post-translationally modified by the lipoperoxidation product 4-hydroxynonenal (4-HNE).
[src:protein/actin-p02] This modification prevents the remodelling of the actin cytoskeleton, which is essential for cell motility.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Additionally, another functional protein, coronin-1A, which stabilizes F-actin filaments, is also covalently modified by 4-HNE.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Actin is used in scientific and technological laboratories as a track for molecular motors such as myosin (either in muscle tissue or outside it) and as a necessary component for cellular functioning.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It can also be used as a diagnostic tool, as several of its anomalous variants are related to the appearance of specific pathologies.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The use of actin as an internal control is based on the assumption that its expression is practically constant and independent of experimental conditions.
[src:protein/actin-p02] By comparing the expression of the gene of interest to that of the actin, it is possible to obtain a relative quantity that can be compared between different experiments, whenever the expression of the latter is constant.
[src:protein/actin-p02] It is worth pointing out that actin does not always have the desired stability in its gene expression.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Actin was first observed experimentally in 1887 by W.D.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Halliburton, who extracted a protein from muscle that 'coagulated' preparations of myosin that he called "myosin-ferment".
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, Halliburton was unable to further refine his findings, and the discovery of actin is credited instead to Brunó Ferenc Straub, a young biochemist working in Albert Szent-Györgyi's laboratory at the Institute of Medical Chemistry at the University of Szeged, Hungary.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Following up on the discovery of Ilona Banga & Szent-Györgyi in 1941 that the coagulation only occurs in some myosin extractions and was reversed upon the addition of ATP, Straub identified and purified actin from those myosin preparations that did coagulate.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Building on Banga's original extraction method, he developed a novel technique for extracting muscle protein that allowed him to isolate substantial amounts of relatively pure actin, published in 1942.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Straub's method is essentially the same as that used in laboratories today.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Since Straub's protein was necessary to activate the coagulation of myosin, it was dubbed *actin*.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Realizing that Banga's coagulating myosin preparations contained actin as well, Szent-Györgyi called the mixture of both proteins actomyosin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The hostilities of World War II meant Szent-Gyorgyi was unable to publish his lab's work in Western scientific journals.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Actin therefore only became well known in the West in 1945, when their paper was published as a supplement to the *Acta Physiologica Scandinavica*.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Straub continued to work on actin, and in 1950 reported that actin contains bound ATP and that, during polymerization of the protein into microfilaments, the nucleotide is hydrolyzed to ADP and inorganic phosphate (which remain bound to the microfilament).
[src:protein/actin-p02] Straub suggested that the transformation of ATP-bound actin to ADP-bound actin played a role in muscular contraction.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In fact, this is true only in smooth muscle, and was not supported through experimentation until 2001.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The amino acid sequencing of actin was completed by M.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The crystal structure of G-actin was solved in 1990 by Kabsch and colleagues.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In the same year, a model for F-actin was proposed by Holmes and colleagues following experiments using co-crystallization with different proteins.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The procedure of co-crystallization with different proteins was used repeatedly during the following years, until in 2001 the isolated protein was crystallized along with ADP.
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, there is still no high-resolution X-ray structure of F-actin.
[src:protein/actin-p02] The crystallization of G-actin was possible due to the use of a rhodamine conjugate that impedes polymerization by blocking the amino acid cys-374.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Christine Oriol-Audit died in the same year that actin was first crystallized but she was the researcher that in 1977 first crystallized actin in the absence of Actin Binding Proteins (ABPs).
[src:protein/actin-p02] However, the resulting crystals were too small for the available technology of the time.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Although no high-resolution model of actin's filamentous form currently exists, in 2008 Sawaya's team were able to produce a more exact model of its structure based on multiple crystals of actin dimers that bind in different places.
[src:protein/actin-p02] This model has subsequently been further refined by Sawaya and Lorenz.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Other approaches such as the use of cryo-electron microscopy and synchrotron radiation have recently allowed increasing resolution and better understanding of the nature of the interactions and conformational changes implicated in the formation of actin filaments.
[src:protein/actin-p02] A number of natural toxins that interfere with actin's dynamics are widely used in research to study actin's role in biology.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Latrunculin – a toxin produced by sponges – binds to G-actin preventing it from joining microfilaments.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Cytochalasin D – produced by certain fungi – serves as a capping factor, binding to the (+) end of a filament and preventing further addition of actin molecules.
[src:protein/actin-p02] In contrast, the sponge toxin jasplakinolide promotes the nucleation of new actin filaments by binding and stabilizing pairs of actin molecules.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Phalloidin – from the "death cap" mushroom *Amanita phalloides* – binds to adjacent actin molecules within the F-actin filament, stabilizing the filament and preventing its depolymerization.
[src:protein/actin-p02] Phalloidin is often labelled with fluorescent dyes to visualize actin filaments by fluorescence microscopy.
[src:protein/active-site] In biology and biochemistry, the **active site** is the region of an enzyme where substrate molecules bind and undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] The active site consists of amino acid residues that form temporary bonds with the substrate, the *binding site*, and residues that catalyse a reaction of that substrate, the ***catalytic site***.
[src:protein/active-site] Although the active site occupies only ~10–20% of the volume of an enzyme, it is the most important part as it directly catalyzes the chemical reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] It usually consists of three to four amino acids, while other amino acids within the protein are required to maintain the tertiary structure of the enzymes.
[src:protein/active-site] Each active site is evolved to be optimised to bind a particular substrate and catalyse a particular reaction, resulting in high specificity.
[src:protein/active-site] This specificity is determined by the arrangement of amino acids within the active site and the structure of the substrates.
[src:protein/active-site] Sometimes enzymes also need to bind with some cofactors to fulfil their function.
[src:protein/active-site] The active site is usually a groove or pocket of the enzyme which can be located in a deep tunnel within the enzyme, or between the interfaces of multimeric enzymes.
[src:protein/active-site] An active site can catalyse a reaction repeatedly as residues are not altered at the end of the reaction (they may change during the reaction, but are regenerated by the end).
[src:protein/active-site] This process is achieved by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, so more substrates have enough energy to undergo reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] Usually, an enzyme molecule has only one active site, and the active site fits with one specific type of substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] An active site contains a binding site that binds the substrate and orients it for catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] The orientation of the substrate and the close proximity between it and the active site is so important that in some cases the enzyme can still function properly even though all other parts are mutated and lose function.
[src:protein/active-site] Initially, the interaction between the active site and the substrate is non-covalent and transient.
[src:protein/active-site] There are four important types of interaction that hold the substrate in a defined orientation and form an enzyme-substrate complex (ES complex): hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions, hydrophobic interactions and electrostatic force interactions.
[src:protein/active-site] The charge distribution on the substrate and active site must be complementary, which means all positive and negative charges must be cancelled out.
[src:protein/active-site] Otherwise, there will be a repulsive force pushing them apart.
[src:protein/active-site] The active site usually contains non-polar amino acids, although sometimes polar amino acids may also occur.
[src:protein/active-site] The binding of substrate to the binding site requires at least three contact points in order to achieve stereo-, regio-, and enantioselectivity.
[src:protein/active-site] For example, alcohol dehydrogenase which catalyses the transfer of a hydride ion from ethanol to NAD+ interacts with the substrate methyl group, hydroxyl group and the pro-*(R)* hydrogen that will be abstracted during the reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] In order to exert their function, enzymes need to assume their correct protein fold (*native fold*) and tertiary structure.
[src:protein/active-site] To maintain this defined three-dimensional structure, proteins rely on various types of interactions between their amino acid residues.
[src:protein/active-site] If these interactions are interfered with, for example by extreme pH values, high temperature or high ion concentrations, this will cause the enzyme to denature and lose its catalytic activity.
[src:protein/active-site] A tighter fit between an active site and the substrate molecule is believed to increase the efficiency of a reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] If the tightness between the active site of DNA polymerase and its substrate is increased, the fidelity, which means the correct rate of DNA replication will also increase.
[src:protein/active-site] Most enzymes have deeply buried active sites, which can be accessed by a substrate via access channels.
[src:protein/active-site] There are three proposed models of how enzymes fit their specific substrate: the lock and key model, the induced fit model, and the conformational selection model.
[src:protein/active-site] The latter two are not mutually exclusive: conformational selection can be followed by a change in the enzyme's shape.
[src:protein/active-site] Additionally, a protein may not wholly follow either model.
[src:protein/active-site] Amino acids at the binding site of ubiquitin generally follow the induced fit model, whereas the rest of the protein generally adheres to conformational selection.
[src:protein/active-site] Factors such as temperature likely influences the pathway taken during binding, with higher temperatures predicted to increase the importance of conformational selection and decrease that of induced fit.
[src:protein/active-site] This concept was suggested by the 19th-century chemist Emil Fischer.
[src:protein/active-site] He proposed that the active site and substrate are two stable structures that fit perfectly without any further modification, just like a key fits into a lock.
[src:protein/active-site] If one substrate perfectly binds to its active site, the interactions between them will be strongest, resulting in high catalytic efficiency.
[src:protein/active-site] As time went by, limitations of this model started to appear.
[src:protein/active-site] For example, the competitive enzyme inhibitor methylglucoside can bind tightly to the active site of 4-alpha-glucanotransferase and perfectly fits into it.
[src:protein/active-site] However, 4-alpha-glucanotransferase is not active on methylglucoside and no glycosyl transfer occurs.
[src:protein/active-site] The Lock and Key hypothesis cannot explain this, as it would predict a high efficiency of methylglucoside glycosyl transfer due to its tight binding.
[src:protein/active-site] Apart from competitive inhibition, this theory cannot explain the mechanism of action of non-competitive inhibitors either, as they do not bind to the active site but nevertheless influence catalytic activity.
[src:protein/active-site] Daniel Koshland's theory of enzyme-substrate binding is that the active site and the binding portion of the substrate are not exactly complementary.
[src:protein/active-site] The induced fit model is a development of the lock-and-key model and assumes that an active site is flexible and changes shape until the substrate is completely bound.
[src:protein/active-site] This model is similar to a person wearing a glove: the glove changes shape to fit the hand.
[src:protein/active-site] The enzyme initially has a conformation that attracts its substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] Enzyme surface is flexible and only the correct catalyst can induce interaction leading to catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] Conformational changes may then occur as the substrate is bound.
[src:protein/active-site] After the reaction products will move away from the enzyme and the active site returns to its initial shape.
[src:protein/active-site] This hypothesis is supported by the observation that the entire protein domain could move several nanometers during catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] This movement of protein surface can create microenvironments that favour the catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] This model suggests that enzymes exist in a variety of conformations, only some of which are capable of binding to a substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] When a substrate is bound to the protein, the equilibrium in the conformational ensemble shifts towards those able to bind ligands (as enzymes with bound substrates are removed from the equilibrium between the free conformations).
[src:protein/active-site] Positively charged sodium ion and negatively charged fluoride ion attract each other to form sodium fluoride under electrostatic interaction.
[src:protein/active-site] Hydrogen bond between two water molecules.
[src:protein/active-site] Van der Waals force between two acetone molecules.
[src:protein/active-site] The lower acetone molecule contains a partially negative oxygen atom that attracts partially positive carbon atom in the upper acetone.
[src:protein/active-site] Hydrophobic and hydrophilic groups tend to assemble with the same kind of molecules.
[src:protein/active-site] Once the substrate is bound and oriented to the active site, catalysis can begin.
[src:protein/active-site] The residues of the catalytic site are typically very close to the binding site, and some residues can have dual-roles in both binding and catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] During enzyme catalytic reaction, the substrate and active site are brought together in a close proximity.
[src:protein/active-site] Firstly, when substrates bind within the active site the effective concentration of it significantly increases than in solution.
[src:protein/active-site] This means the number of substrate molecules involved in the reaction is also increased.
[src:protein/active-site] This process also reduces the desolvation energy required for the reaction to occur.
[src:protein/active-site] In solution substrate molecules are surrounded by solvent molecules and energy is required for enzyme molecules to replace them and contact with the substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] Since bulk molecules can be excluded from the active site this energy output can be minimised.
[src:protein/active-site] Next, the active site is designed to reorient the substrate to reduce the activation energy for the reaction to occur.
[src:protein/active-site] The alignment of the substrate, after binding, is locked in a high energy state and can proceed to the next step.
[src:protein/active-site] In addition, this binding is favoured by entropy as the energy cost associated with solution reaction is largely eliminated since solvent cannot enter active site.
[src:protein/active-site] In the end, the active site may manipulate the Molecular orbital of the substrate into a suitable orientation to reduce activation energy.
[src:protein/active-site] The electrostatic states of substrate and active site must be complementary to each other.
[src:protein/active-site] A polarized negatively charged amino acid side chain will repel uncharged substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] But if the transition state involves the formation of an ion centre then the side chain will now produce a favourable interaction.
[src:protein/active-site] Many enzymes including serine protease, cysteine protease, protein kinase and phosphatase evolved to form transient covalent bonds between them and their substrates to lower the activation energy and allow the reaction to occur.
[src:protein/active-site] This process can be divided into 2 steps: formation and breakdown.
[src:protein/active-site] The former step is rate-limit step while the later step is needed to regenerate intact enzyme.
[src:protein/active-site] Metal ions have multiple roles during the reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] Firstly it can bind to negatively charged substrate groups so they will not repel electron pairs from active site's nucleophilic groups.
[src:protein/active-site] It can attract negatively charged electrons to increase electrophilicity.
[src:protein/active-site] It can also bridge between active site and substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] At last, they may change the conformational structure of the substrate to favour reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] In some reactions, protons and hydroxide may directly act as acid and base in term of specific acid and specific base catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] But more often groups in substrate and active site act as Brønsted–Lowry acid and base.
[src:protein/active-site] This is called general acid and general base theory.
[src:protein/active-site] The easiest way to distinguish between them is to check whether the reaction rate is determined by the concentrations of the general acid and base.
[src:protein/active-site] If the answer is yes then the reaction is the general type.
[src:protein/active-site] Since most enzymes have an optimum pH of 6 to 7, the amino acids in the side chain usually have a p*K*a of 4~10.
[src:protein/active-site] Candidate include aspartate, glutamate, histidine, cysteine.
[src:protein/active-site] These acids and bases can stabilise the nucleophile or electrophile formed during the catalysis by providing positive and negative charges.
[src:protein/active-site] Quantitative studies of enzymatic reactions often found that the acceleration of chemical reaction speed cannot be fully explained by existing theories like the approximation, acid/base catalysis and electrophile/nucleophile catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] And there is an obvious paradox: in reversible enzymatic reaction if the active site perfectly fits the substrates then the backward reaction will be slowed since products cannot fit perfectly into the active site.
[src:protein/active-site] So conformational distortion was introduced and argues that both active site and substrate can undergo conformational changes to fit with each other all the time.
[src:protein/active-site] This theory is a little similar to the Lock and Key Theory, but at this time the active site is preprogrammed to bind perfectly to substrate in transition state rather than in ground state.
[src:protein/active-site] The formation of transition state within the solution requires a large amount of energy to relocate solvent molecules and the reaction is slowed.
[src:protein/active-site] So the active site can substitute solvent molecules and surround the substrates to minimize the counterproductive effect imposed by the solution.
[src:protein/active-site] The presence of charged groups with the active site will attract substrates and ensure electrostatic complementarity.
[src:protein/active-site] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:protein/active-site] The role of glutathione(GSH) is to remove accumulated reactive oxygen species which may damage cells.
[src:protein/active-site] During this process, its thiol side chain is oxidised and two glutathione molecules are connected by a disulphide bond to form a dimer(GSSG).
[src:protein/active-site] In order to regenerate glutathione the disulphide bond has to be broken, In human cells, this is done by glutathione reductase(GR).
[src:protein/active-site] Glutathione reductase is a dimer that contains two identical subunits.
[src:protein/active-site] It requires one NADP and one FAD as the cofactors.
[src:protein/active-site] The active site is located in the linkage between two subunits.
[src:protein/active-site] The NADPH is involved in the generation of FADH-.
[src:protein/active-site] In the active site, there are two cysteine residues besides the FAD cofactor and are used to break the disulphide bond during the catalytic reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] NADPH is bound by three positively charged residues: Arg-218, His-219 and Arg-224.
[src:protein/active-site] The catalytic process starts when the FAD is reduced by NADPH to accept one electron and from FADH−.
[src:protein/active-site] It then attacks the disulphide bond formed between 2 cysteine residues, forming one SH bond and a single S− group.
[src:protein/active-site] This S− group will act as a nucleophile to attack the disulphide bond in the oxidised glutathione(GSSG), breaking it and forming a cysteine-SG complex.
[src:protein/active-site] The first SG− anion is released and then receives one proton from adjacent SH group and from the first glutathione monomer.
[src:protein/active-site] Next the adjacent S− group attack disulphide bond in cysteine-SG complex and release the second SG− anion.
[src:protein/active-site] It receives one proton in solution and forms the second glutathione monomer.
[src:protein/active-site] Chymotrypsin is a serine endopeptidase that is present in pancreatic juice and helps the hydrolysis of proteins and peptide.
[src:protein/active-site] It catalyzes the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in L-isomers of tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:protein/active-site] In the active site of this enzyme, three amino acid residues work together to form a catalytic triad which makes up the catalytic site.
[src:protein/active-site] In chymotrypsin, these residues are Ser-195, His-57 and Asp-102.
[src:protein/active-site] The mechanism of chymotrypsin can be divided into two phases.
[src:protein/active-site] First, Ser-195 nucleophilically attacks the peptide bond carbon in the substrate to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:protein/active-site] The nucleophilicity of Ser-195 is enhanced by His-57, which abstracts a proton from Ser-195 and is in turn stabilised by the negatively charged carboxylate group (RCOO−) in Asp-102.
[src:protein/active-site] Furthermore, the tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate generated in this step is stabilised by hydrogen bonds from Ser-195 and Gly-193.
[src:protein/active-site] In the second stage, the R'NH group is protonated by His-57 to form R'NH2 and leaves the intermediate, leaving behind the acylated Ser-195.
[src:protein/active-site] His-57 then acts as a base again to abstract one proton from a water molecule.
[src:protein/active-site] The resulting hydroxide anion nucleophilically attacks the acyl-enzyme complex to form a second tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate, which is once again stabilised by H bonds.
[src:protein/active-site] In the end, Ser-195 leaves the tetrahedral intermediate, breaking the CO bond that connected the enzyme to the peptide substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] A proton is transferred to Ser-195 through His-57, so that all three amino acid return to their initial state.
[src:protein/active-site] Substrate unbinding is influenced by various factors.
[src:protein/active-site] Larger ligands generally stay in the active site longer, as do those with more rotatable bonds (although this may be a side effect of size).
[src:protein/active-site] When the solvent is excluded from the active site, less flexible proteins result in longer residence times.
[src:protein/active-site] More hydrogen bonds shielded from the solvent also decrease unbinding.
[src:protein/active-site] Enzymes can use cofactors as 'helper molecules'.
[src:protein/active-site] Coenzymes are referred to those non-protein molecules that bind with enzymes to help them fulfill their jobs.
[src:protein/active-site] Mostly they are connected to the active site by non-covalent bonds such as hydrogen bond or hydrophobic interaction.
[src:protein/active-site] But sometimes a covalent bond can also form between them.
[src:protein/active-site] For example, the heme in cytochrome C is bound to the protein through thioester bond.
[src:protein/active-site] In some occasions, coenzymes can leave enzymes after the reaction is finished.
[src:protein/active-site] Otherwise, they permanently bind to the enzyme.
[src:protein/active-site] Coenzyme is a broad concept which includes metal ions, various vitamins and ATP.
[src:protein/active-site] If an enzyme needs coenzyme to work itself, it is called an apoenzyme.
[src:protein/active-site] In fact, it alone cannot catalyze reactions properly.
[src:protein/active-site] Only when its cofactor comes in and binds to the active site to form holoenzyme does it work properly.
[src:protein/active-site] It contains a distinct conjugated isoalloxazine ring system.
[src:protein/active-site] Flavin has multiple redox states and can be used in processes that involve the transfer of one or two electrons.
[src:protein/active-site] It can act as an electron acceptor in reaction, like the oxidation of NAD to NADH, to accept two electrons and form 1,5-dihydroflavin.
[src:protein/active-site] On the other hand, it can form semiquinone(free radical) by accepting one electron, and then converts to fully reduced form by the addition of an extra electron.
[src:protein/active-site] This property allows it to be used in one electron oxidation process.
[src:protein/active-site] Inhibitors disrupt the interaction between enzyme and substrate, slowing down the rate of a reaction.
[src:protein/active-site] There are different types of inhibitor, including both reversible and irreversible forms.
[src:protein/active-site] Competitive inhibitors are inhibitors that only target free enzyme molecules.
[src:protein/active-site] They compete with substrates for free enzyme acceptor and can be overcome by increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:protein/active-site] Competitive inhibitors usually have structural similarities to the substrates and or ES complex.
[src:protein/active-site] As a result, they can fit into the active site and trigger favourable interactions to fill in the space and block substrates from entry.
[src:protein/active-site] They can also induce transient conformational changes in the active site so substrates cannot fit perfectly with it.
[src:protein/active-site] After a short period of time, competitive inhibitors will drop off and leave the enzyme intact.
[src:protein/active-site] Inhibitors are classified as non-competitive inhibitors when they bind both free enzyme and ES complex.
[src:protein/active-site] Since they do not compete with substrates for the active site, they cannot be overcome by simply increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:protein/active-site] They usually bind to a different site on the enzyme and alter the 3-dimensional structure of the active site to block substrates from entry or leaving the enzyme.
[src:protein/active-site] Irreversible inhibitors are similar to competitive inhibitors as they both bind to the active site.
[src:protein/active-site] However, irreversible inhibitors form irreversible covalent bonds with the amino acid residues in the active site and never leave.
[src:protein/active-site] Therefore, the active site is occupied and the substrate cannot enter.
[src:protein/active-site] Occasionally the inhibitor will leave but the catalytic site is permanently altered in shape.
[src:protein/active-site] These inhibitors usually contain electrophilic groups like halogen substitutes and epoxides.
[src:protein/active-site] As time goes by more and more enzymes are bound by irreversible inhibitors and cannot function anymore.
[src:protein/active-site] HIV protease inhibitors are used to treat patients having AIDS virus by preventing its DNA replication.
[src:protein/active-site] HIV protease is used by the virus to cleave Gag-Pol polyprotein into 3 smaller proteins that are responsible for virion assembly, package and maturation.
[src:protein/active-site] This enzyme targets the specific phenylalanine-proline cleave site within the target protein.
[src:protein/active-site] If HIV protease is switched off the virion particle will lose function and cannot infect patients.
[src:protein/active-site] Since it is essential in viral replication and is absent in healthy human, it is an ideal target for drug development.
[src:protein/active-site] HIV protease belongs to aspartic protease family and has a similar mechanism.
[src:protein/active-site] Firstly the aspartate residue activates a water molecule and turns it into a nucleophile.
[src:protein/active-site] Then it attacks the carbonyl group within the peptide bond (NH-CO) to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:protein/active-site] The nitrogen atom within the intermediate receives a proton, forming an amide group and subsequent rearrangement leads to the breakdown of the bond between it and the intermediate and forms two products.
[src:protein/active-site] Inhibitors usually contain a nonhydrolyzable hydroxyethylene or hydroxyethylamine groups that mimic the tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:protein/active-site] Since they share a similar structure and electrostatic arrangement to the transition state of substrates they can still fit into the active site but cannot be broken down, so hydrolysis cannot occur.
[src:protein/active-site] Strychnine is a neurotoxin that causes death by affecting nerves that control muscular contraction and cause respiration difficulty.
[src:protein/active-site] The impulse is transmitted between the synapse through a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine.
[src:protein/active-site] It is released into the synapse between nerve cells and binds to receptors in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:protein/active-site] Then an action potential is generated and transmitted through the postsynaptic cell to start a new cycle.
[src:protein/active-site] Glycine can inhibit the activity of neurotransmitter receptors, thus a larger amount of acetylcholinesterase is required to trigger an action potential.
[src:protein/active-site] This makes sure that the generation of nerve impulses is tightly controlled.
[src:protein/active-site] However, this control is broken down when strychnine is added.
[src:protein/active-site] It inhibits glycine receptors(a chloride channel) and a much lower level of neurotransmitter concentration can trigger an action potential.
[src:protein/active-site] Nerves now constantly transmit signals and cause excessive muscular contraction, leading to asphyxiation and death.
[src:protein/active-site] Diisopropyl fluorophosphate (DIFP) is an irreversible inhibitor that blocks the action of serine protease.
[src:protein/active-site] When it binds to the enzyme a nucleophilic substitution reaction occurs and releases one hydrogen fluoride molecule.
[src:protein/active-site] The OH group in the active site acts as a nucleophile to attack the phosphorus in DIFP and form a tetrahedral intermediate and release a proton.
[src:protein/active-site] Then the P-F bond is broken, one electron is transferred to the F atom and it leaves the intermediate as F− anion.
[src:protein/active-site] It combines with a proton in solution to form one HF molecule.
[src:protein/active-site] A covalent bond formed between the active site and DIFP, so the serine side chain is no longer available to the substrate.
[src:protein/active-site] Identification of active sites is crucial in the process of drug discovery.
[src:protein/active-site] The 3-D structure of the enzyme is analysed to identify active site residues and design drugs which can fit into them.
[src:protein/active-site] Proteolytic enzymes are targets for some drugs, such as protease inhibitors, which include drugs against AIDS and hypertension.
[src:protein/active-site] These protease inhibitors bind to an enzyme's active site and block interaction with natural substrates.
[src:protein/active-site] An important factor in drug design is the strength of binding between the active site and an enzyme inhibitor.
[src:protein/active-site] If the enzyme found in bacteria is significantly different from the human enzyme then an inhibitor can be designed against that particular bacterium without harming the human enzyme.
[src:protein/active-site] If one kind of enzyme is only present in one kind of organism, its inhibitor can be used to specifically wipe them out.
[src:protein/active-site] Active sites can be mapped to aid the design of new drugs such as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:protein/active-site] This involves the description of the size of an active site and the number and properties of sub-sites, such as details of the binding interaction.
[src:protein/active-site] Modern database technology called CPASS (Comparison of Protein Active Site Structures) however allows the comparison of active sites in more detail and the finding of structural similarity using software.
[src:protein/active-site] An allosteric site is a site on an enzyme, unrelated to its active site, which can bind an effector molecule.
[src:protein/active-site] This interaction is another mechanism of enzyme regulation.
[src:protein/active-site] Allosteric modification usually happens in proteins with more than one subunit.
[src:protein/active-site] Allosteric interactions are often present in metabolic pathways and are beneficial in that they allow one step of a reaction to regulate another step.
[src:protein/active-site] They allow an enzyme to have a range of molecular interactions, other than the highly specific active site.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:protein/adaptive-immune-system] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:protein/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:protein/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:protein/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:protein/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:protein/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:protein/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:protein/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:protein/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:protein/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:protein/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:protein/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:protein/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:protein/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:protein/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:protein/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:protein/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:protein/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:protein/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:protein/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:protein/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:protein/protein] A linear chain of amino acid residues is called a polypeptide.
[src:protein/protein] A protein contains at least one long polypeptide.
[src:protein/protein] Short polypeptides, containing less than 20–30 residues, are rarely considered to be proteins and are commonly called peptides.
[src:protein/protein] The individual amino acid residues are bonded together by peptide bonds and adjacent amino acid residues.
[src:protein/protein] The sequence of amino acid residues in a protein is defined by the sequence of a gene, which is encoded in the genetic code.
[src:protein/protein] In general, the genetic code specifies 20 standard amino acids; but in certain organisms the genetic code can include selenocysteine and—in certain archaea—pyrrolysine.
[src:protein/protein] Shortly after or even during synthesis, the residues in a protein are often chemically modified by post-translational modification, which alters the physical and chemical properties, folding, stability, activity, and ultimately, the function of the proteins.
[src:protein/protein] Some require a non-protein chemical compound or ion for biological activity, these are known as cofactors.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins can work together to achieve a particular function, and they often associate to form stable protein complexes.
[src:protein/protein] Once formed, proteins only exist for a certain period and are then degraded and recycled by the cell's machinery through the process of protein turnover.
[src:protein/protein] A protein's lifespan is measured in terms of its half-life and covers a wide range.
[src:protein/protein] They can exist for minutes or years with an average lifespan of 1–2 days in mammalian cells.
[src:protein/protein] Abnormal or misfolded proteins are degraded more rapidly, often by the proteasome, which is a large protein assembly itself.
[src:protein/protein] These proteins are degraded either due to being targeted (ubiquitin ligases can mark a protein for destruction) or due to being unstable or damaged.
[src:protein/protein] Like other biological macromolecules such as polysaccharides and nucleic acids, proteins are essential parts of organisms and participate in virtually every process within cells.
[src:protein/protein] Many proteins are enzymes that catalyse biochemical reactions and are vital to metabolism.
[src:protein/protein] Some proteins have structural or mechanical functions, such as actin and myosin in muscle, and the cytoskeleton's scaffolding proteins that maintain cell shape.
[src:protein/protein] Other proteins are important in cell signaling, immune responses, cell adhesion, and the cell cycle.
[src:protein/protein] In animals, proteins are needed in the diet to provide the essential amino acids that cannot be made.
[src:protein/protein] Dietary proteins are digested into amino acids to replenish the body's free amino acid pool, which is mostly used to make new body proteins, but is also critically important for energy production and to make other vital nitrogen-containing molecules.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins have been studied and recognized since the 1700s by Antoine Fourcroy and others, who often collectively called them "albumins", or "albuminous materials" (*Eiweisskörper*, in German).
[src:protein/protein] Gluten, for example, was first separated from wheat in published research around 1747, and later determined to exist in many plants.
[src:protein/protein] In 1789, Antoine Fourcroy recognized three distinct varieties of animal proteins: albumin, fibrin, and gelatin.
[src:protein/protein] Vegetable (plant) proteins studied in the late 1700s and early 1800s included gluten, plant albumin, gliadin, and legumin.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins were first described by the Dutch chemist Gerardus Johannes Mulder and named by the Swedish chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius in 1838.
[src:protein/protein] Mulder carried out elemental analysis of common proteins and found that nearly all proteins had the same empirical formula, C400H620N100O120P1S1.
[src:protein/protein] He came to the erroneous conclusion that they might be composed of a single type of (very large) molecule.
[src:protein/protein] The term "protein" to describe these molecules was proposed by Mulder's associate Berzelius; protein is derived from the Greek word πρώτειος (*proteios*), meaning "primary", "in the lead", or "standing in front", + *-in*.
[src:protein/protein] Mulder went on to identify the products of protein degradation such as the amino acid leucine for which he found a (nearly correct) molecular weight of 131 Da.
[src:protein/protein] Early nutritional scientists such as the German Carl von Voit believed that protein was the most important nutrient for maintaining the structure of the body, because it was generally believed that "flesh makes flesh".
[src:protein/protein] Around 1862, Karl Heinrich Ritthausen isolated the amino acid glutamic acid.
[src:protein/protein] Thomas Burr Osborne compiled a detailed review of the vegetable proteins at the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station.
[src:protein/protein] Osborne, alongside Lafayette Mendel, established several nutritionally essential amino acids in feeding experiments with laboratory rats.
[src:protein/protein] Diets lacking an essential amino acid stunts the rats' growth, consistent with Liebig's law of the minimum.
[src:protein/protein] The final essential amino acid to be discovered, threonine, was identified by William Cumming Rose.
[src:protein/protein] The difficulty in purifying proteins impeded work by early protein biochemists.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins could be obtained in large quantities from blood, egg whites, and keratin, but individual proteins were unavailable.
[src:protein/protein] In the 1950s, the Armour Hot Dog Company purified 1 kg of bovine pancreatic ribonuclease A and made it freely available to scientists.
[src:protein/protein] This gesture helped ribonuclease A become a major target for biochemical study for the following decades.
[src:protein/protein] The understanding of proteins as polypeptides, or chains of amino acids, came through the work of Franz Hofmeister and Hermann Emil Fischer in 1902.
[src:protein/protein] The central role of proteins as enzymes in living organisms that catalyzed reactions was not fully appreciated until 1926, when James B.
[src:protein/protein] Sumner showed that the enzyme urease was in fact a protein.
[src:protein/protein] Linus Pauling is credited with the successful prediction of regular protein secondary structures based on hydrogen bonding, an idea first put forth by William Astbury in 1933.
[src:protein/protein] Later work by Walter Kauzmann on denaturation, based partly on previous studies by Kaj Linderstrøm-Lang, contributed an understanding of protein folding and structure mediated by hydrophobic interactions.
[src:protein/protein] The first protein to have its amino acid chain sequenced was insulin, by Frederick Sanger, in 1949.
[src:protein/protein] Sanger correctly determined the amino acid sequence of insulin, thus conclusively demonstrating that proteins consisted of linear polymers of amino acids rather than branched chains, colloids, or cyclols.
[src:protein/protein] He won the Nobel Prize for this achievement in 1958.
[src:protein/protein] Christian Anfinsen's studies of the oxidative folding process of ribonuclease A, for which he won the nobel prize in 1972, solidified the thermodynamic hypothesis of protein folding, according to which the folded form of a protein represents its free energy minimum.
[src:protein/protein] With the development of X-ray crystallography, it became possible to determine protein structures as well as their sequences.
[src:protein/protein] The first protein structures to be solved were hemoglobin by Max Perutz and myoglobin by John Kendrew, in 1958.
[src:protein/protein] The use of computers and increasing computing power has supported the sequencing of complex proteins.
[src:protein/protein] In 1999, Roger Kornberg sequenced the highly complex structure of RNA polymerase using high intensity X-rays from synchrotrons.
[src:protein/protein] Since then, cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) of large macromolecular assemblies has been developed.
[src:protein/protein] Cryo-EM uses protein samples that are frozen rather than crystals, and beams of electrons rather than X-rays.
[src:protein/protein] It causes less damage to the sample, allowing scientists to obtain more information and analyze larger structures.
[src:protein/protein] Computational protein structure prediction of small protein structural domains has helped researchers to approach atomic-level resolution of protein structures.
[src:protein/protein] As of April 2024, the Protein Data Bank contains 181,018 X-ray, 19,809 EM and 12,697 NMR protein structures.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins are primarily classified by sequence and structure, although other classifications are commonly used.
[src:protein/protein] Especially for enzymes the EC number system provides a functional classification scheme.
[src:protein/protein] Similarly, gene ontology classifies both genes and proteins by their biological and biochemical function, and by their intracellular location.
[src:protein/protein] Sequence similarity is used to classify proteins both in terms of evolutionary and functional similarity.
[src:protein/protein] This may use either whole proteins or protein domains, especially in multi-domain proteins.
[src:protein/protein] Protein domains allow protein classification by a combination of sequence, structure and function, and they can be combined in many ways.
[src:protein/protein] In an early study of 170,000 proteins, about two-thirds were assigned at least one domain, with larger proteins containing more domains (e.g. proteins larger than 600 amino acids having an average of more than 5 domains).
[src:protein/protein] Most proteins consist of linear polymers built from series of up to 20 L-α-amino acids.
[src:protein/protein] All proteinogenic amino acids have a common structure where an α-carbon is bonded to an amino group, a carboxyl group, and a variable side chain.
[src:protein/protein] Only proline differs from this basic structure as its side chain is cyclical, bonding to the amino group, limiting protein chain flexibility.
[src:protein/protein] The side chains of the standard amino acids have a variety of chemical structures and properties, and it is the combined effect of all amino acids that determines its three-dimensional structure and chemical reactivity.
[src:protein/protein] The amino acids in a polypeptide chain are linked by peptide bonds between amino and carboxyl group.
[src:protein/protein] An individual amino acid in a chain is called a *residue*, and the linked series of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen atoms are known as the *main chain* or *protein backbone*.
[src:protein/protein] The peptide bond has two resonance forms that confer some double-bond character to the backbone.
[src:protein/protein] The alpha carbons are roughly coplanar with the nitrogen and the carbonyl (C=O) group.
[src:protein/protein] The other two dihedral angles in the peptide bond determine the local shape assumed by the protein backbone.
[src:protein/protein] One consequence of the N-C(O) double bond character is that proteins are somewhat rigid.
[src:protein/protein] A polypeptide chain ends with a free amino group, known as the *N-terminus* or *amino terminus*, and a free carboxyl group, known as the *C-terminus* or *carboxy terminus*.
[src:protein/protein] By convention, peptide sequences are written N-terminus to C-terminus, correlating with the order in which proteins are synthesized by ribosomes.
[src:protein/protein] The words *protein*, *polypeptide*, and *peptide* are a little ambiguous and can overlap in meaning.
[src:protein/protein] *Protein* is generally used to refer to the complete biological molecule in a stable conformation, whereas *peptide* is generally reserved for a short amino acid oligomers often lacking a stable 3D structure.
[src:protein/protein] But the boundary between the two is not well defined and usually lies near 20–30 residues.
[src:protein/protein] Proteins can interact with many types of molecules and ions, including with other proteins, with lipids, with carbohydrates, and with DNA.
[src:protein/protein] *E. coli* and *Staphylococcus aureus*, is estimated to contain about 2 million proteins.
[src:protein/protein] Smaller bacteria, such as *Mycoplasma* or spirochetes contain fewer molecules, on the order of 50,000 to 1 million.
[src:protein/protein] By contrast, eukaryotic cells are larger and thus contain much more protein.
[src:protein/protein] For instance, yeast cells have been estimated to contain about 50 million protein molecules and human cells on the order of 1 to 3 billion.
